  "prompt": "Will our current scientific theories (especially evolutionary) be outdated in 100+ years?",
  "response": "That's a great philosophical question about scientific knowledge. Most historians and philosophers of science would likely say:\n\n1. Some core principles will probably remain robust:\n- Basic mechanisms of evolution by natural selection\n- Fundamental physics and chemistry principles\n- Broad strokes of cosmological understanding\n\n2. Significant refinements are likely in:\n- Detailed mechanisms of genetic inheritance\n- Precise models of evolutionary processes\n- Quantum mechanics interpretations\n- Understanding of complex biological systems\n\n3. Potential paradigm shifts could occur in:\n- Origin of life theories\n- Deeper understanding of consciousness\n- Complexity of genetic interactions\n- Potential discovery of currently unknown physical laws\n\n4. Historical precedent suggests:\n- Scientific theories regularly get modified/replaced\n- Current theories are more sophisticated than 100 years ago\n- Science is a self-correcting process\n\nThe scientific consensus is that while specific details will change, foundational theories like evolution have extremely strong empirical support. Major revolutions are possible but unlikely to completely invalidate core principles.\n\nMost scientists view current theories as our best current understanding, always open to refinement with new evidence.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more about how scientific knowledge evolves?",
